Data Cleaning

acad_perf <- read.csv("/Users/rioffe/Desktop/Statistics/Stat 414/acad_perf.csv",header=TRUE)
#head(acad_perf, 10)
acad_perf1 <- acad_perf %>%
      mutate(Semester = if_else(Semester == "F", "First", "Second")) %>%
        mutate(gender = if_else(gender == "M", "Male", "Female"))
acad_perf1 <- acad_perf1 %>%
   mutate(result = ifelse(Class == "M", 1,
                          ifelse(Class == "H", 1,
                          ifelse(Class == "L", 0, 0))))
summary_hands <- acad_perf1 %>%
   group_by(PlaceofBirth) %>%
      summarise(avg_hands = round(mean(raisedhands), 2), 
                sd_hands = sd(raisedhands), 
                n = n())
 
#head(summary_hands,5)


acad_perf1 <- acad_perf1 %>%
      group_by(PlaceofBirth) %>%
      mutate(avg_hands = round(mean(raisedhands),2))

#head(acad_perf1,5)
acad_perf1 <- acad_perf1 %>%
  mutate(grouping = paste(GradeID,SectionID, sep = "" ))

#1. Exploring Variability

#Plot of variability in response variable across the level 2 units

#level 2 units: Grouping Variable

library(ggeffects)

boxplot(acad_perf1$raisedhands ~ acad_perf1$grouping)

plot(ggeffects::ggpredict(model1, terms=c("raisedhands", "grouping [sample = 9]"), type = "re"), ci = FALSE)
## Data were 'prettified'. Consider using `terms="raisedhands [all]"` to
##   get smooth plots.

#Fit an Chi-SQ using ols for response variable and the level-2 grouping variable to test for signifigance of grouping variable.

#choosing between gradeID and semester

chisq.test(acad_perf1$result, acad_perf1$grouping)
## Warning in chisq.test(acad_perf1$result, acad_perf1$grouping): Chi-squared
## approximation may be incorrect
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  acad_perf1$result and acad_perf1$grouping
## X-squared = 29.409, df = 16, p-value = 0.02132

The group effect seems to be statistically significant. We fit an ANOVA for the grouping variable - combining grade level and section to test its significance. To begin exploring variation in one of our explanatory variables, raisedhands, we aggregated two separate level two variables called grade and section into a single level two variable, grouping using the paste function in R. The box plot of raised hands by grouping indicates considerable variation in the distribution of the raisedhands variable across the different groups.

Some groups (like G-02A, G-02C) show a lower median and a narrower interquartile range (IQR), indicating less variability and generally lower raisedhands counts. Other groups, like G-08B and G-11A, show a higher median and a wider IQR, indicating more variability and higher raisedhands counts. Outliers are present in group 11B as indicated by the dots outside the whiskers of the box plots.

We also examined the predicted probabilities of result by grade grouping. The predicted probabilities completely converged.

As raisedhands increases, the probability of the positive result also increases for all groups, but this effect seems consistent across the groups since the lines are parallel. This implies that the effect of raisedhands on the result does not differ by group in the model.

We had a chisq value of 29.409 , with a p-value of 0.02132, so we can conclude that grouping effect is statistically significant.

#2. Fitting the intercepts only model.

intercepts_model <- glmer(result ~ 1 + (1|grouping), family = "binomial", data = acad_perf1)
summary(intercepts_model)

##   Approximation) [glmerMod]

## Number of obs: 480, groups:  grouping, 17

## (Intercept)   1.0715     0.1507   7.108 1.18e-12 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
performance(intercepts_model)

ICC: 0.0326

The ICC is 0.0326, so 3.26% of the total variability in the the result can be attributed to differences between the groups identified by the grouping variable. The relatively small ICC suggests that while there is some variability in the results between groups, most of the variability is within the groups or due to other factors not included in the model - or is explained by our raised hands variable. Therefore - it does not seem quite substantial - however, the grouping variable was significant.

Fixed Effects Estimate of Intercept: 1.0715

The estimated fixed effect for the intercept is 1.0715. In the context of a logistic regression model, this parameter represents the log odds of the outcome variable when all predictors are at their reference levels - or, at the average log odds of passing/failing a class across the grouping variable with grade level and section.

Variance of Random Effects of Grouping Variable: 0.1108

The variance of the random intercepts is 0.1108 - this means that the variability of the log odds of the result in the class being success between the different levels of the grouping variable is about 0.1108.

P-value: 2.2e^-16

Where df is the difference in the number of terms between each model. Where the p-value is found from the Chi-Squared p-value in ANOVA comparison output.

From the model summary output, we can see that all of the added level 1 variables in the model: parent school satisfaction, measured as a categorical good or bad, and Student absence days, categorical under-7 or over-7 are significant in explaining variation in student result in the class. Therefore, we decided to keep these variables in the model to help explain some of the level 1 variation in student pass/fail result as there is not a lot of level 2 variation in the grouping variable. With the addition of these level one variables into the model, the level 2 variation increased from 0.1108 in the intercepts-only model to 0.2608 in the model containing our level 1 variables. This would mean that adding parent school satisfaction and student absences into the model would explain some level 1 variation in student academic result, however, these variables would provide information that would contribute to group-to-group variation in average result - providing more higher than average or lower than average estimates.

In the anova output comparing model8 and model8b, we can see that the model with raised hands has much lower AIC and BIC values. Therefore, we know that adding raised hands back into the model will increase model performance in predicting class result significantly.

Proportion of Variation Explained:

Model 8:

random effects grouping variance: 0 intercept standard error: 0.368110

Model 8b:

random effects grouping variance: 0.2608 intercept standard error: 0.2746

Intercepts-only model:

random effects grouping variance: 0.1108 intercept standard error: 0.1507

Adding level one variables into the model increased the group-to-group level 2 variance in average pass/fail class results by about 35.38%. It did not explain any variation in the level 2 grouping variable. Adding level one variables into the model also increased the variation in average pass/fail class results by about 17.8% for the average Class/section group.

Adding raised hands back into the model causes the level 2 variation in pass/fail results to be essentially 0. This means that raised hands accounts for most of the variation in pass/fail results - therefore - level 2 variation in Class/section grouping is essentially 0.

AIC BIC model8 244.69 265.56
model9 328.56 357.78 model9b. 325.50 346.37 model9c 246.6 271.7

From the anova LRT output comparing model8 and model9, with the added level 2 variables, we can see that adding level 2 variables into the model does not improve model performance - based on the large p-value from the Chisq output. Therefore, we decided that adding level 2 variables into the model will not significantly improve model performance. Neither the StageID variable, explaining High, Middle, or Elementary school, or Semester, first or second, was significant in model summary output. However, semester seemed to have a small p-value of 0.8049. The AIC values for model 8 were without level 2 variables were lower than the AIC values for models with added level 2 variables. Therefore, we decided to get rid of all level 2 added variables in our final model.

Proportion of Variance Explained:

Model 8b:

random effects grouping variance: 0.2608 intercept standard error: 0.2746

Model 9: grouping: 0.1202 intercept: 0.64620

Adding level 2 variables into the model explained about 53.91% of the variation in average class pass/fail result in the level 2 grouping variable. Also, these variables explained no variation in average pass/fail results in the average group. These were the comparisons without raised hands added into the model. When we add raised hands back into the model, the grouping variance again becomes 0 and the standard error of the intercept decreases as well.

When adding random slopes on the level 1 variable discussion - which indicates the amount of times that students participated in class discussions - across the grouping variable, we saw that this model was significantly better then the model without random slopes on this variable. From the anova chisq p-value of 0.006 and a df of 2, adding random slopes on the discussion variable is a significant improvement compared to the model without random slopes.

The random slopes plot shows significant variability in the slopes of discussion across groups. There are a few negative slopes, positive slopes, and varying slope steepness across the groups.

The amount of group-to-group variability in the slopes is about 0.001652. Or, the average effect of participating in a discussion across values of the grouping variable, grade and section levels of students, on pass/fail result varies by about 0.001652 log odds.

finalmodel <- glmer(result ~ raisedhands + ParentschoolSatisfaction + StudentAbsenceDays + (Discussion|grouping) + Discussion*Semester, family = "binomial", data = acad_perf1)
## Warning in checkConv(attr(opt, "derivs"), opt$par, ctrl = control$checkConv, :
## Model failed to converge with max|grad| = 0.0781944 (tol = 0.002, component 1)

Some variation in discussion across semester was explained by the interaction term Discussion*Semester. Although the interaction term was not significant, the relatively small p-value of 0.08282 from the anova comparison of the model with and without the interaction term suggests that this interaction explains some, but not a significant amount, of variation in random slopes for discussion across semester.

Interpret Interaction:

The coefficient for the interaction term Discussion*Semester is 0.013035. This means that when school is in the Second Semester, the effect of semester on how many times a student participates in a discussion during class increases - keeping constant parental satisfaction, student absence and at the average discussion participation.

This model is not significantly better in explaining slope variation than the model in step 5 - however, the anova comparison did produce a relatively small p-vaue of 0.08282.

## centering the raisedhands variable

# Calculate the mean of the raisedhands variable
mean_raisedhands <- mean(acad_perf1$raisedhands)

# Create a centered variable with the name 'raisedhands_centered'
raisedhands_centered <- acad_perf1$raisedhands - mean_raisedhands

# Optionally, if we want to add it back to our dataframe:
acad_perf1$raisedhands_centered <- raisedhands_centered

library(ggplot2)
# using binary result

ggplot(acad_perf1, aes(x = as.factor(result), y = raisedhands)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ result) +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Raised Hands by Result",
       x = "Result (0 = Fail, 1 = Pass)",
       y = "Raised Hands") +
  theme_minimal()

# using categorical Class

ggplot(acad_perf1, aes(x = Class, y = raisedhands, fill = Class)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Raised Hands by Pass/Fail",
       x = "Class (Pass/Fail)",
       y = "Raised Hands") +
  theme_minimal()

Histogram of Raised Hands for Pass/Fail Classes

ggplot(acad_perf1, aes(x = raisedhands, fill = result)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, position = "identity", alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Raised Hands",
       x = "Raised Hands",
       y = "Count") +
  facet_wrap(~ result) +
  theme_minimal()

##Exploration into switching explanatory and response variables

#Switching Response and Explanatory Variables Exploration
modelb1 <- lmer(raisedhands ~ Topic + result + (1 | GradeID), data = acad_perf1)
#summary(model10)

# Model 11: influence of StageID and Result on raised hands
modelb2 <- lmer(raisedhands ~ StageID + result + (1 | PlaceofBirth), data = acad_perf1)
#summary(model11)

# Model 12: combined impact of Topic, Result, and Grade on raised hands
modelb3 <- lmer(raisedhands ~ Topic + result + (1 | GradeID), data = acad_perf1)
#summary(model12)

#correlation matrix for data

library(ggcorrplot)
model.matrix(~0+., data = acad_perf1[9:19]) %>%
  cor(use = "pairwise.complete.obs") %>%
  ggcorrplot(show.diag = FALSE, type = "lower", lab = TRUE, lab_size = 2)
